iPhone camera settings ð¥

Note : You can use these settings for Android too!

1. Record at 4k/30fps : I prefer to shoot in 4k/30fps because it gives the best quality as well as cinematic feel to any video. Because of 30fps we can see natural motion blur so it looks good for cinematic videos.

2. Turn âAUTO HDRâ off : While HDR can enhance your shots by blending different exposures, sometimes it can make photos look unnatural. The newer iPhone models tend to have a high-clarity appearance, making the images look overly pixelated or manipulated. Itâs a clinical-type look that many digital cameras replicate. Many professional photographers agree that the intention of this effect doesnât look great,
so we suggest turning the HDR off for a cleaner, true-to-life tone. 

3. Use given âZOOM PRESETSâ : As apple provided these 3 zoom presets for some reason right? As these presets doesnât make your footage degrade the quality. It tries to give the best out of it but if we use eg: 1.2x or 2.6x then these zooms can degrade the quality.

4. Use âGRIDSâ : A well-composed shot can make all the difference. The Rule of Thirds is a photography principle that helps balance your image, making it more appealing. It splits your frame into nine even parts using horizontal and vertical lines. You craft a more harmonious and captivating image by aligning your primary subject or crucial elements on these lines or where they meet. This method is a favorite among photographers to steer the viewerâs gaze and infuse depth and layers into the composition. 

5. Adjust âEXPOSURE MANUALLYâ : Auto-exposure doesnât always get it right, even on expensive camera rigs. Adjusting yourself can help capture your scene just as you envision it. Doing this can greatly affect the mood of your image and make for an easier time in the editing room (I.e., not having to worry about blown-out highlights).
